[2] Saudi Arabia: WHO update 7 Nov 2014
Date: Fri 7 Nov 2014
Source: WHO Global Alert and Response (GAR), Disease Outbreak News (DONs) [edited]
http://who.int/csr/don/07-november-2014-mers/en/


Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) -- Saudi Arabia 7 Nov 2014
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Between 27 and 30 Oct 2014, the National IHR Focal Point of Saudi Arabia (KSA) notified WHO of 12 additional cases of Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) infection, including 3 deaths.

Details of the cases are as follows:
The cases are from Riyadh (5), Taif (4), Hafr Albatin (1), Jouf (1), and Makkah (1). The median age of the patients is 56 years old (ranging from 30 to 90 years old). 8 cases (67 percent) are men and 8 (67 percent) are Saudi nationals. 11 cases (92 percent) suffer from 1 or more comorbidities. In the 14 days that preceded the onset of symptoms, none of the cases performed Umrah/Hajj [pilgrimage] nor travelled out of their cities of residence. Only 1 case (8 percent) has a history of contact with animals and of raw camel products consumption. 7 cases (67 percent) -- 2 of which were healthcare professionals -- came in contact with MERS-CoV patients. 2 cases (17 percent) -- including 1 healthcare worker -- spent time at hospitals with ongoing MERS-CoV outbreaks, although they had no contact with infected patients.

Tracing of household contacts and healthcare contacts is ongoing for these cases.

The National IHR Focal Point of Saudi Arabia also notified WHO of the death of 3 MERS-CoV cases that were reported between 7 and 24 Oct 2014.

Globally, WHO has been notified of 909 laboratory-confirmed cases of infection with MERS-CoV, including at least 331 related deaths.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Marianne Hopp

[The 12 laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV reported during the period 27 to 30 Oct 2014 mentioned above were reported previously on ProMED-mail (see references below). Additional information in the report above relates to possible high risk exposures in the healthcare environment on the part of 9 of the 12 cases (75 percent) with 7 giving a definite history of contact with suspected or confirmed cases, and an additional 2 who had been in facilities with active MERS-CoV cases, although direct contact was not identified.

With the addition of these 12 cases, the global total of laboratory confirmed MERS-CoV infected individuals is now at 909 including "at least" 331 related deaths (case fatality rate 36.4 percent). The most recent global tally maintained by the ECDC has reports of 929 cases including 372 deaths (case fatality rate 40.0 percent) as of 5 Nov 2014 (http://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/press/news/_layouts/forms/News_DispForm.aspx?List=8db7286c-fe2d-476c-9133-18ff4cb1b568&ID=1102).

For the HealthMap/ProMED map of Saudi Arabia see https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2938223,131. - Mod.MPP]

