[4] Saudi Arabia (Riyadh): MOH outbreak control 6 Nov 2014
Date: Thu 6 Nov 2014
Source: Saudi Arabia Ministry of Health, press release [edited]
http://www.moh.gov.sa/en/Ministry/MediaCenter/News/Pages/News-2014-11-06-001.aspx


Ministry of Health responds to MERS-CoV cases in Riyadh 6 Nov 2014
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Ministry of Health continues to manage MERS-CoV cases associated with the cluster in Taif, including 5 confirmed cases in Riyadh that originated with a patient who traveled there last month [October 2014] from Taif.

Four people, including patients and healthcare workers, tested positive for MERS-CoV after coming into contact with the index patient, who was admitted on [18 Oct 2014] to Dr Sulaiman Al-Habib Hospital in Riyadh. 2 of those patients later died. One recovered and was discharged, another remains hospitalized at a MERS-CoV Center of Excellence.

The Ministry's Command & Control Center (CCC) identified the cases through its disease surveillance system and immediately dispatched a rapid-response team to assess the infection prevention and control (IPC) procedures at the hospital. In addition to conducting inspections, the Ministry identified patients and healthcare workers who had contact with the index patient for evaluation and follow up. More than 200 people, including family members and healthcare workers, were tested for the virus.

"MERS-CoV is active and we need to be on full alert," Dr Anees Sindi, Deputy Commander of the CCC, said. "Healthcare workers can reduce the risk of infection by continuing to take all the required precautions to protect themselves and their patients."

The CCC is working with the World Health Organization to investigate the Taif cluster that is associated with these cases.

"Hemodialysis patients have a compromised immune system, putting them at higher risk of developing more complications from MERS-CoV than the average patient," said Dr Abdullah Assiri, the Assistant Deputy Minister for Preventive Health and liaison to the WHO. "Hospitals should be very vigilant in monitoring these patients and isolating them when they develop any symptoms that may be attributed to an infection."

Drs Sindi and Assiri visited the hospital immediately after the 1st case was diagnosed to provide support and guidance. CCC continues to monitor the situation along with public-health and infection-control experts from the Ministry. After the CCC submitted its recommendations, the regional directorate assigned a team to the hospital to ensure that infection control practices were being followed and the recommendations were being implemented.

In partnership with the WHO and US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), the Ministry has instituted a number of reforms designed to protect patients and healthcare workers from MERS-CoV infection. This includes fit-testing healthcare workers for masks and providing ongoing education about the guidelines for identifying and treating patients suspected of having MERS-CoV.

Whenever possible, MERS-CoV patients are transferred to a specially designated facility. Prince Mohammed bin Abdulaziz Hospital is the Center of Excellence for the Central Region.

The Ministry has developed new policies and trained thousands of healthcare workers on how to reduce the risk of hospital-acquired infection. More than 30 research projects are underway in partnership with local and international scientists, including a critical case-control study designed to identify causes of MERS-CoV infection in Saudi Arabia.

There have been at least 796 confirmed cases of MERS-CoV in Saudi Arabia since June 2012. Please visit the CCC website, http://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CCC/Pages/default.aspx, for the latest statistics and to learn more about how to reduce the risk of infection.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The MOH press releases above are confirmation of the relationship between the outbreak in Taif and the outbreak in Riyadh. It is clear that there are extensive investigations ongoing to trace chains of transmission of the MERS-CoV within the country.

The mention that over 200 individuals were tested for MERS-CoV as part of evaluations of contacts of confirmed cases in the outbreak in Taif raises the question of whether only symptomatic cases are being reported. Previously there had been reports of asymptomatic MERS-CoV infected individuals identified through contact tracing and testing.

Since 1 Sep 2014, there have been a total of 56 laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection reported in Saudi Arabia with 22 reported in Taif and 21 cases reported in Riyadh during this time period (since the beginning of September 2014). The mention that 1/3 of cases reported in Taif had a history of contact with camels or camel products prior to onset of illness is new -- according to the original MOH reports 11 (50 percent) of the cases in Taif had possible exposure in the health care environment (either healthcare workers or stated exposure) and only 2 of the cases were reported to have had a history of exposures to camels.

It is also of interest to learn that there are case control studies underway to identify high risk exposures for transmission of the virus. We look forward to seeing the results of these studies. - Mod.MPP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2938223,131.]
